      <h2><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ocean" target="_blank">Oceans</a></h2>
      <ul>
        <li>The Pacific Ocean is the largest ocean on Earth.</li>
        <li>The Great Barrier Reef in Australia is the largest coral reef system in the world.</li>
        <li>The Mariana Trench in the Pacific Ocean is the deepest part of the Earth's oceans.</li>
        <li>The Atlantic Ocean is the saltiest ocean due to high evaporation rates.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="nature_card_item">
      <h2><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Forest" target="_blank">Forests</a></h2>
      <ul>
        <li>The Amazon Rainforest is the largest tropical rainforest in the world.</li>
        <li>Forests are home to more than half of the world's terrestrial species.</li>
        <li>Forests act as a carbon sink, helping to mitigate climate change by absorbing carbon dioxide.</li>
        <li>The Taiga, also known as the boreal forest, is the largest terrestrial biome.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="nature_card" id="mountains">
    <div class="nature_card_item">
      <h2><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mountain" target="_blank">Mountains</a></h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Mount Everest is the highest peak in the world, standing at 8,848 meters (29,029 feet).</li>
        <li>The Himalayas are the highest mountain range, stretching across several countries including Nepal, India, and Bhutan.</li>
        <li>The Andes in South America is the longest mountain range, extending over 7,000 kilometers (4,350 miles).</li>
        <li>Mount Kilimanjaro in Tanzania is the highest freestanding mountain in the world.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="nature_card_item">
      <h2><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Desert" target="_blank">Deserts</a></h2>
      <ul>
        <li>The Sahara Desert in Africa is the largest hot desert in the world.</li>
        <li>The Atacama Desert in Chile is one of the driest places on Earth.</li>
        <li>The Gobi Desert in Asia is the largest desert in Asia.</li>
        <li>The Namib Desert in Namibia is known for its stunning sand dunes.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="nature_card" id="rivers">
  <div class="nature_card_item">
    <h2><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/River" target="_blank">Rivers</a></h2>
    <ul>
      <li>The Nile River in Africa is the longest river in the world, stretching over 6,650 kilometers (4,130 miles).</li>
      <li>The Amazon River in South America is the largest river by discharge volume and water flow.</li>
      <li>The Mississippi River in the United States is one of the longest rivers in North America.</li>
      <li>The Ganges River in India is considered sacred by Hindus and is known for its cultural and religious significance.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
  <div class="nature_card_item">
    <h2><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Caves" target="_blank">Caves</a></h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Mammoth Cave in the United States is the longest known cave system in the world, with over 650 kilometers (400 miles) of explored passages.</li>
      <li>The Waitomo Glowworm Caves in New Zealand are famous for their unique glowworm population that illuminates the caves.</li>
      <li>The Eisriesenwelt Ice Cave in Austria is the largest ice cave in the world.</li>
      <li>The Caves of Cappadocia in Turkey feature ancient cave dwellings carved into the soft volcanic rock.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="nature_card" id="wildlife">
